  "prompt": "What is a summary of \"SparkNotes: Bread Givers\"?",
  "response": "\"SparkNotes: Bread Givers\" provides a detailed summary of Anzia Yezierska's novel \"Bread Givers.\" The story revolves around the struggles and aspirations of Sara Smolinsky, a young Jewish girl growing up in New York City's Lower East Side in the 1920s. The novel explores themes of independence, family duty, and immigrant life. \n\nSara's father, Reb Smolinsky, is an orthodox rabbi who rigidly upholds traditional values and expects his daughters to support the family while obeying his will. Reb's authoritarian rule conflicts with Sara's desire for education and self-reliance. Throughout the novel, Sara fights for her right to carve out her own identity, eventually leaving her family to pursue an education and a career.\n\nDespite the hardships and emotional turmoil she faces, Sara remains determined to achieve her dreams. The novel captures the tensions between old-world traditions and new-world ambitions, highlighting the generational and cultural conflicts within immigrant families adapting to American life.",
